1️⃣ Evolution of Pain (Why Consistent Hashing Exists)

Imagine you built a distributed system.

You have 3 database servers:

DB1
DB2
DB3

You store users based on hash(key) % number_of_servers.

Example:

userId = 25
hash(25) % 3 = 1

So the data goes to:

DB1

Everything works perfectly.

💥 Disaster Scenario

Now traffic increases.

You add another server.

DB1
DB2
DB3
DB4

Your hashing changes:

hash(key) % 4

Now the result for every key changes.

Example:

UserID	Old Server	New Server
25	DB1	DB2
31	DB2	DB4
45	DB3	DB1

Result:

💥 Almost all data needs to move.

This is called massive rebalancing.

For millions of records this becomes extremely expensive.

This exact problem happens in:

distributed databases

caching systems (Redis cluster)

load balancers

CDNs

2️⃣ The Cure (Consistent Hashing)

Consistent hashing solves the problem by ensuring:

Adding or removing a server
moves only a small portion of keys.

Instead of rebalancing all data, we rebalance only nearby keys.

Goal:

Minimize data movement
3️⃣ The Core Idea (Hash Ring)

Instead of using:

hash(key) % N

We create a circular ring.

Example:

Range:

0 → 2^32

or simplified:

0 → 12

Visual idea:

      0
   /     \
 11       1
 |         |
10         2
 |         |
 9         3
   \     /
      6

This is called a hash ring.

4️⃣ Step 1 — Place Servers on the Ring

Each server is hashed.

Example:

hash(DB1) → position 2
hash(DB2) → position 6
hash(DB3) → position 10

Ring becomes:

      0
   /     \
 11       1
 |        DB1(2)
10 DB3     3
 |         |
 9         4
   \     /
      DB2(6)
5️⃣ Step 2 — Place Keys on the Ring

Each key is also hashed.

Example:

hash(user1) → 3
hash(user2) → 7
hash(user3) → 11
6️⃣ Step 3 — Assign Keys to Servers

Rule:

Move clockwise until a server is found

Example:

Key Position	Assigned Server
3	DB2
7	DB3
11	DB1

So:

user1 → DB2
user2 → DB3
user3 → DB1
7️⃣ What Happens When a Server Is Added

Suppose we add:

DB4 → position 8

Only keys between:

DB2 → DB4

move.

Example:

user2 moves from DB3 → DB4

Everything else stays the same.

So instead of:

100% data movement

We get roughly:

1/N data movement
8️⃣ What Happens When a Server Is Removed

If DB2 crashes:

Only keys between:

DB2 → DB3

move.

Example:

user1 moves from DB2 → DB3

Everything else stays unchanged.

This is why consistent hashing is very powerful.

9️⃣ Real Problem — Uneven Distribution

Servers might hash unevenly.

Example ring:

DB1 at 2
DB2 at 3
DB3 at 10

Large section goes to DB3.

Result:

DB3 overloaded
🔟 Solution — Virtual Nodes

Each server is placed multiple times on the ring.

Example:

DB1 → positions 2, 8, 11
DB2 → positions 4, 6, 10
DB3 → positions 1, 7, 9

Now distribution becomes balanced.

Example:

user1 → DB2
user2 → DB3
user3 → DB1
user4 → DB2

This prevents hotspot servers.

1️⃣1️⃣ Where Consistent Hashing Is Used
1️⃣ Distributed Databases

Example:

Cassandra

DynamoDB

Riak

Used for sharding data.

2️⃣ Caching Systems

Example:

Redis Cluster

Memcached

Cache keys distributed across nodes.

3️⃣ Load Balancers

Load balancer maps:

request → server

using consistent hashing.

4️⃣ CDNs

Example:

Akamai

Cloudflare

Consistent hashing decides:

which CDN node stores which content
1️⃣2️⃣ Real World Analogy

Imagine a pizza restaurant chain around a circular road.

Each restaurant covers the next section clockwise.

Customers go to the nearest clockwise restaurant.

If a new restaurant opens:

Only customers nearby switch restaurants.

Everyone else stays the same.

This is exactly consistent hashing.

1️⃣3️⃣ Trade-Off Sandbox
❓ What if we use simple hashing?
hash(key) % servers

Problem:

Adding server = move almost all data

Very expensive.

❓ What if we don't use virtual nodes?

Problem:

Uneven load
Server hotspots
❓ What if a server crashes?

Consistent hashing ensures:

Only nearby keys move

System remains stable.

1️⃣4️⃣ HLD Interview Insight

If interviewer asks:

How do distributed caches rebalance data when nodes are added?

Answer:

Consistent Hashing

Mention:

hash ring

clockwise assignment

virtual nodes

minimal data movement

1️⃣5️⃣ Connection to Your Previous Topics

Consistent hashing connects with many things you've learned:

Concept	Connection
Horizontal Sharding	Distribute DB rows
Load Balancer	Assign requests
CDN	Assign content to nodes
Redis Cache	Key distribution

✅ PK, once you understand Consistent Hashing + Sharding + Caching + Load Balancer, you basically understand the core scaling mechanics of large systems.